Blogger, humorist and math student Siyanda Mohutsiwa explores African topics both weighty (reviving Pan­Africanism) and witty (“5 things NOT to say when trying to seduce an Afrikaner”). Her columns for African media outlets like the Mail & Guardian, Za News, and her own website Siyanda Writes have gained a loyal following. 

But when Mohutsiwa’s hashtag #IfAfricaWasABar exploded on Twitter, the viral thread (which pondered the hypothetical bar mannerisms of various African nations) became a platform for everyday Africans to unite in a playful dialogue on national differences, and helped turn Mohutsiwa into a social media star.

aws-transcripts.transcript: it began with one question. If Africa was about what was your country be drinking or doing? I kicked it off with a guest of our South Africa, which wasn't exactly according to the rules, because South Africa is not my country but alluding to the country's continual attempts to build a post racial society after being ravaged by decades by apartheid, I treated if Africa was a bar, South Africa would be drinking all kinds of alcohol and begging them to get along in its stomach. And then I waited. Then I have that funny feeling where I wondered if I crossed the line. So I sent out a few other treats about my own country and a few other African countries I'm familiar with. And then I waited again. But this time I read through almost every treat I had ever treated to convince myself no to remind myself that I'm really funny and that if nobody gets it, that's fine. But luckily I don't have to do that for very large. Very soon, people were participating. In fact, by the end of that week in July, the hashtag, if Africa was a bar, would have gone around 60,000 tweets lit off the continent and made its way to publications all over the world, people were using the hashtag to do many different things to poke fun at the stereotypes, to criticize government spending to make light of geopolitical tensions, to remind us that even in Africa there's some countries we don't know exist and also to make fun of the countries that don't think that they're in Africa. Yeah, and to note the countries that had made a big turnaround. But most importantly, people were using the hash tag to connect. People were connecting over the African nous. So for one week in July, Twitter became a riel African bar. And I was really thrilled. Maybe because I realized that Pan Africanism could work, that we had before us between us at our fingertips, a platform that just needed a small spark to light in us. Ah, hunger for each other.
